# Day 12 – Salesforce DX Workflow

## What is Salesforce DX?

Salesforce DX (Developer Experience) is a modern development framework provided by Salesforce that enables source-driven development, team collaboration, version control, and automated deployment processes.

Salesforce DX helps developers build, test, and deploy applications more efficiently using tools such as Scratch Orgs, Salesforce CLI, and Git-based workflows.

### Key Features of Salesforce DX

* Source-driven development
* Scratch Orgs
* Salesforce CLI
* Version control integration
* Continuous Integration and Continuous Deployment (CI/CD)
* Team collaboration support

### Benefits

* Faster development cycles
* Better code management
* Improved deployment processes
* Easier collaboration among teams
* Higher software quality

---

# Why CLI Matters

CLI (Command Line Interface) is one of the most important components of Salesforce DX.

The Salesforce CLI allows developers to interact with Salesforce environments directly from the terminal without using the graphical interface.

### Common CLI Commands

#### Create a Scratch Org

```bash id="8o7vpx"
sf org create scratch
```

#### Deploy Source

```bash id="9pshn0"
sf project deploy start
```

#### Run Apex Tests

```bash id="x5o9bq"
sf apex run test
```

#### Retrieve Metadata

```bash id="4kw47j"
sf project retrieve start
```

### Why CLI is Important

* Automates repetitive tasks
* Increases developer productivity
* Enables CI/CD pipelines
* Supports scripting and automation
* Reduces manual deployment errors

### Enterprise Benefits

Organizations can automate development and deployment activities, improving consistency and efficiency.

